<div id="review_3657748383" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3657748383" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3657748383?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=american-fiction-since-2010">american-fiction-since-2010</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=american-fiction">american-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3657748383" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15661910018671763530">I&apos;d found Shalom Auslander&apos;s memoir of an Orthodox Jewish childhood compelling, if flawed, and his authorial voice was something I thought I&apos;d liked. Maybe not. What I got in Hope: A Tragedy was a “magical realist” novel of the worst kind, one in which – and mea culpa, there&apos;s no better way to put it – a very deliberately and profoundly Jewy protagonist man&apos;s neuroses culminate in Anne Frank hiding out in his attic. That actually would have been a decent conceit for a 30-page short story, but st</span>
  <span id="freeText15661910018671763530" style="display:none">I'd found Shalom Auslander's memoir of an Orthodox Jewish childhood compelling, if flawed, and his authorial voice was something I thought I'd liked. Maybe not. What I got in Hope: A Tragedy was a “magical realist” novel of the worst kind, one in which – and mea culpa, there's no better way to put it – a very deliberately and profoundly Jewy protagonist man's neuroses culminate in Anne Frank hiding out in his attic. That actually would have been a decent conceit for a 30-page short story, but stretched out over a novel, it grates with all manner of middle-class hemming and hawing (and he could have done so, so much more with the omnipresence of Alan Dershowitz, that's an opportunity for prime-cut satire right there). To provide a contrast, I loved spending two hours with Alvie Singer in Annie Hall (because when Jewish neuroses enter the conversation, Woody Allen is bound to as well). Hell I went as Alvie Singer for Halloween one year, with a nice young woman who made a very convincing Annie. However, Alvie Singer had more vulnerability and humanity in two hours than Auslander could muster in a 400-page novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15661910018671763530" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

