    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_349806951" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/349806951" />
    <a title="Frieda Vizel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6192529-frieda-vizel"><img alt="Frieda Vizel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603728771p2/6192529.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/349806951?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frieda Vizel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frieda Vizel" href="/user/show/6192529-frieda-vizel">Frieda Vizel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer349806951" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15135152700122197234">This book is an original, well written work that had me laughing out loud many times. I give Auslander 4 stars for creativity and witticism, but I give 2 for plot and other elements. After about 1/3 of the book the funny bits get recycled and the plot becomes very thin. A lot of his jokes turn up six times in the same book! Lines like: &apos;Live each day as something, go enjoy the whatever, stop to smell the what-have-you&apos; that mock cliches are funny at first but after a few times feel very old and </span>
  <span id="freeText15135152700122197234" style="display:none">This book is an original, well written work that had me laughing out loud many times. I give Auslander 4 stars for creativity and witticism, but I give 2 for plot and other elements. After about 1/3 of the book the funny bits get recycled and the plot becomes very thin. A lot of his jokes turn up six times in the same book! Lines like: 'Live each day as something, go enjoy the whatever, stop to smell the what-have-you' that mock cliches are funny at first but after a few times feel very old and forced. The story is very over the top and hard to believe. For example, Kugel, the tragic main character, seems to struggle with problems that are easily avoidable, and because it is hard to understand why Kugel doesn't simply solve his problems, it is impossible to sympathize with him. As the book keeps going and Kugel single handedly ruins his life for inexplicable reasons, the story losses steam. It is hard to watch the self destruction when it seems as absurd and unlikely. Kugel buys a mattress for his unwelcome attic guest (a living Anne Frank) despite his desperate financial situation, prompting his wife to leave him. It is hard to understand why he does it when neither Anne Frank wanted it nor he could afford it. The "Jewish holocaust guilt" motive is so stretched at this point, it's impossible to buy.<br /><br />You cannot read this work without admiring Auslander's perceptiveness and intelligence. It is clear that he has an original, often dark, but always fascinated view on mankind and Jewish culture. Unfortunately, I think he took it all too far in his book. If he had given Kugel a better motive or altered the plot to make the story more believable, everything would have come together much better.<br /><br />I know from reading Auslander's other works that he has some strong opinions about post-holocaust Jewish culture. According to his experience, Jews in America often imparted to their children such severe ideas of guilt as if to make up for their lack of suffering by punishing themselves and their family. That whole aspect of his writing is really interesting and new to me.<br /><br />In the book there are way too many references to bodily functions for my liking. I suppose some find toilet humor funny, I found it a distraction.<br /><br />An interesting thing about the book: dialog is not in quotations. Talk about taking creative licenses! I liked it!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15135152700122197234" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

